<ol class='feature list_items no_numbers' data-display-style='feature' data-number-style='no_numbers'>
<li class='row list_item clearfix ' id='id-563cca6f9724b200010000d2'>
<figure class='media photo horizontal' data-media-action='modal'>
<span class='visually-hidden'>
Photo
</span>
<div class='image'>
<img alt='' class='media-viewer-candidate' data-mediaviewer-caption='' data-mediaviewer-credit='From "A Bear&#x0027;s Year"' data-mediaviewer-src='https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/08/books/review/08bear-1/08bear-1-jumbo.jpg' data-pattern='https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/08/books/review/08bear-1/08bear-1-{{size}}.jpg' data-ratio='0.5' data-widths='[{"slug":"master1050","size":1050},{"slug":"master180","size":180},{"slug":"blog225","size":225},{"slug":"tmagSF","size":362},{"slug":"blog427","size":427},{"slug":"blog480","size":480},{"slug":"master495","size":495},{"slug":"blog533","size":533},{"slug":"tmagArticle","size":592},{"slug":"articleLarge","size":600},{"slug":"master675","size":675},{"slug":"jumbo","size":1024},{"slug":"popup","size":650},{"slug":"slide","size":600},{"slug":"superJumbo","size":2048},{"slug":"]","size":null}]' src='https://static01.nyt.com/packages/flash/multimedia/ICONS/transparent.png'>
<div class='media-action-overlay'>
<i class='icon'></i>
</div>
</div>
<figcaption class='caption'>
<span class='credit'>
<span class='visually-hidden'>
Credit
</span>
From "A Bear's Year"
</span>
</figcaption>
</figure>

<div class='listy_headline'>
A Bear’s Year
</div>
<div class='listy_subhead'>
By Kathy Duval. Illustrated by Gerry Turley.
</div>
<div class='listy_body'>
<p>Each time of year has its pleasures in this simple, inviting ramble through the seasons with two brand-new bear cubs and their mother. There’s a long, cozy snooze in winter, fishing and tree-climbing in spring. The parent, we’re reminded, is at work all along: Her cubs “must learn / what Mama knows / while flowers bloom / and grass still grows.” Duval’s concise rhyming nuggets leave space for Turley’s lovely art to conjure a vast yet homey Northern wilderness in soft greens and golden browns. </p>
</div>
<div class='listy_detail'>
<p>32 pp. Schwartz &amp; Wade. $17.99. (Picture book; ages 2 to 6)</p>
</div>
</li>
<li class='row list_item clearfix ' id='id-563cd987a7b41f00010000bc'>
<figure class='media photo horizontal' data-media-action='modal'>
<span class='visually-hidden'>
Photo
</span>
<div class='image'>
<img alt='' class='media-viewer-candidate' data-mediaviewer-caption='' data-mediaviewer-credit='From "Lily and Bear"' data-mediaviewer-src='https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/08/books/review/08bear-2/08bear-2-jumbo.jpg' data-pattern='https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/08/books/review/08bear-2/08bear-2-{{size}}.jpg' data-ratio='0.5458984375' data-widths='[{"slug":"master1050","size":1050},{"slug":"master180","size":180},{"slug":"blog225","size":225},{"slug":"tmagSF","size":362},{"slug":"blog427","size":427},{"slug":"blog480","size":480},{"slug":"master495","size":495},{"slug":"blog533","size":533},{"slug":"tmagArticle","size":592},{"slug":"articleLarge","size":600},{"slug":"master675","size":675},{"slug":"jumbo","size":1024},{"slug":"popup","size":650},{"slug":"slide","size":600},{"slug":"superJumbo","size":2048},{"slug":"]","size":null}]' src='https://static01.nyt.com/packages/flash/multimedia/ICONS/transparent.png'>
<div class='media-action-overlay'>
<i class='icon'></i>
</div>
</div>
<figcaption class='caption'>
<span class='credit'>
<span class='visually-hidden'>
Credit
</span>
From "Lily and Bear"
</span>
</figcaption>
</figure>

<div class='listy_headline'>
Lily and Bear
</div>
<div class='listy_subhead'>
Written and illustrated by Lisa Stubbs
</div>
<div class='listy_body'>
<p>It’s no wonder Lily, who loves to draw all sorts of things, draws a bear who comes to life and becomes her bestie. What matches a bear for sheer huggability, not to mention the awesome ­standing-on-two-feet trick? They play, sing and draw together. But Lily has to learn to be fair and do bear things too, like heading to a tree for a back scratch. This cheerful debut celebrates art and friendship, with unusual screen-printed illustrations that mix cherry-red textile patterns and childlike crayon strokes.</p>
</div>
<div class='listy_detail'>
<p>32 pp. Paula Wiseman/Simon &amp; Schuster. $17.99. (Picture book; ages 3 to 8)</p>
</div>
</li>
<li class='row list_item clearfix ' id='id-563cd9c59724b200010000e6'>
<figure class='media photo horizontal' data-media-action='modal'>
<span class='visually-hidden'>
Photo
</span>
<div class='image'>
<img alt='' class='media-viewer-candidate' data-mediaviewer-caption='' data-mediaviewer-credit='From "I Love You Already!"' data-mediaviewer-src='https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/08/books/review/08bear-3/08bear-3-jumbo.jpg' data-pattern='https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/08/books/review/08bear-3/08bear-3-{{size}}.jpg' data-ratio='0.611328125' data-widths='[{"slug":"master1050","size":1050},{"slug":"master180","size":180},{"slug":"blog225","size":225},{"slug":"tmagSF","size":362},{"slug":"blog427","size":427},{"slug":"blog480","size":480},{"slug":"master495","size":495},{"slug":"blog533","size":533},{"slug":"tmagArticle","size":592},{"slug":"articleLarge","size":600},{"slug":"master675","size":675},{"slug":"jumbo","size":1024},{"slug":"popup","size":650},{"slug":"slide","size":600},{"slug":"superJumbo","size":2048},{"slug":"]","size":null}]' src='https://static01.nyt.com/packages/flash/multimedia/ICONS/transparent.png'>
<div class='media-action-overlay'>
<i class='icon'></i>
</div>
</div>
<figcaption class='caption'>
<span class='credit'>
<span class='visually-hidden'>
Credit
</span>
From "I Love You Already!"
</span>
</figcaption>
</figure>

<div class='listy_headline'>
I Love You Already!
</div>
<div class='listy_subhead'>
By Jory John. Illustrated by Benji Davies.
</div>
<div class='listy_body'>
<p>The last word in this book’s title is meant to be read in a fed-up tone, as in “Goodnight Already!,” the previous story about low-key Bear and his relentless friend Duck. Now all Bear wants is a quiet weekend morning at home in his trademark floral kimono. But Duck wants to “spend some quality time together” (never promising). John’s humor shines; Davies makes the pair’s quirks ridiculously endearing, with Bear’s matted patch of chest fur and Duck’s big fingerlike wings saying everything. </p>
</div>
<div class='listy_detail'>
<p>32 pp. Harper/Harper¬Collins. $17.99. (Picture book; ages 4 to 8)</p>
</div>
</li>
<li class='row list_item clearfix advert_item' id='id-563cda08a7b41f00010000c0'>
<div class='list-ad-container'>
<div class='ad module articlebig mid1 ad-dfp dfp-size-300x250' data-mobile='TopAd1' id='TopAd1'></div>
</div>
</li>
<li class='row list_item clearfix ' id='id-563cda08a7b41f00010000bf'>
<figure class='media photo horizontal' data-media-action='modal'>
<span class='visually-hidden'>
Photo
</span>
<div class='image'>
<img alt='' class='media-viewer-candidate' data-mediaviewer-caption='' data-mediaviewer-credit='From "The Bear Report"' data-mediaviewer-src='https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/08/books/review/08bear-4/08bear-4-jumbo.jpg' data-pattern='https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/08/books/review/08bear-4/08bear-4-{{size}}.jpg' data-ratio='0.5556640625' data-widths='[{"slug":"master1050","size":1050},{"slug":"master180","size":180},{"slug":"blog225","size":225},{"slug":"tmagSF","size":362},{"slug":"blog427","size":427},{"slug":"blog480","size":480},{"slug":"master495","size":495},{"slug":"blog533","size":533},{"slug":"tmagArticle","size":592},{"slug":"articleLarge","size":600},{"slug":"master675","size":675},{"slug":"jumbo","size":1024},{"slug":"popup","size":650},{"slug":"slide","size":600},{"slug":"superJumbo","size":2048},{"slug":"]","size":null}]' src='https://static01.nyt.com/packages/flash/multimedia/ICONS/transparent.png'>
<div class='media-action-overlay'>
<i class='icon'></i>
</div>
</div>
<figcaption class='caption'>
<span class='credit'>
<span class='visually-hidden'>
Credit
</span>
From "The Bear Report"
</span>
</figcaption>
</figure>

<div class='listy_headline'>
The Bear Report
</div>
<div class='listy_subhead'>
Written and illustrated by Thyra Heder
</div>
<div class='listy_body'>
<p>If only all school assignments resulted in a magical visit from the very subject a child is dreading. That’s what happens to ­Sophie, who watches TV and avoids her polar bear report — until giant white Olafur shows up and whisks her off to his frozen home. “It’s better in person,” as he rightly tells her, offended by her bland descriptions. Set over dreamlike watercolors, Heder’s words are all dialogue, comics style, between Sophie and her informative tour guide, who build a heartfelt bond. </p>
</div>
<div class='listy_detail'>
<p>48 pp. Abrams. $17.95. (Picture book; ages 4 to 8)</p>
</div>
</li>
<li class='row list_item clearfix ' id='id-563cda46a7b41f00010000c1'>
<figure class='media photo horizontal' data-media-action='modal'>
<span class='visually-hidden'>
Photo
</span>
<div class='image'>
<img alt='' class='media-viewer-candidate' data-mediaviewer-caption='' data-mediaviewer-credit='From "Finding Winnie"' data-mediaviewer-src='https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/08/books/review/08bear-5/08bear-5-jumbo.jpg' data-pattern='https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/11/08/books/review/08bear-5/08bear-5-{{size}}.jpg' data-ratio='0.5' data-widths='[{"slug":"master1050","size":1050},{"slug":"master180","size":180},{"slug":"blog225","size":225},{"slug":"tmagSF","size":362},{"slug":"blog427","size":427},{"slug":"blog480","size":480},{"slug":"master495","size":495},{"slug":"blog533","size":533},{"slug":"tmagArticle","size":592},{"slug":"articleLarge","size":600},{"slug":"master675","size":675},{"slug":"jumbo","size":1024},{"slug":"popup","size":650},{"slug":"slide","size":600},{"slug":"superJumbo","size":2048},{"slug":"]","size":null}]' src='https://static01.nyt.com/packages/flash/multimedia/ICONS/transparent.png'>
<div class='media-action-overlay'>
<i class='icon'></i>
</div>
</div>
<figcaption class='caption'>
<span class='credit'>
<span class='visually-hidden'>
Credit
</span>
From "Finding Winnie"
</span>
</figcaption>
</figure>

<div class='listy_headline'>
Finding Winnie: The True Story of the World’s Most Famous Bear
</div>
<div class='listy_subhead'>
By Lindsay Mattick. Illustrated by Sophie Blackall.
</div>
<div class='listy_body'>
<p>Gorgeously illustrated by Blackall and written by a great-­granddaughter of the Canadian soldier who bought a bear cub from a trapper and took her to Europe in World War I, this delightful telling of the story behind A. A. Milne’s “Winnie-the-Pooh” is also a family history. Mattick’s son asks for a story; she offers this one — really two: Winnie lands in a zoo, meets Milne’s son, and becomes famous. “Sometimes,” Mattick tells her boy, “you have to let one story end so the next one can begin.” </p>
</div>
<div class='listy_detail'>
<p>32 pp. Little, Brown. $18. (Picture book; ages 4 to 8)</p>
</div>
</li>
</ol>

